        "rule": "Spanish greets differently depending on the time of day, not just how formal you're being. Use buenos días roughly from waking up until midday. Use buenas tardes from midday into early evening, roughly once lunch is behind you until it starts getting dark. Use buenas noches once it's evening or night — and unlike the other two, buenas noches also works as a farewell (“goodnight”), not just a greeting. Exact cutoffs vary by region and person — treat these as “morning / afternoon / evening-night,” not an exact clock. (Optional, for the curious: días is grammatically masculine, which is why it pairs with buenos, while tardes and noches are grammatically feminine and pair with buenas — You'll meet this same masculine/feminine pattern again with the amigo/amiga pattern card later in the unit — here it's just applied to time-of-day nouns instead of people. This isn't about anything being literally male or female — it's just a grammar category Spanish nouns have.)",
