      "audience": "both",
      "flashcard": true,
      "games": [
        "matching"
      ],
      "kid_track": "Usted is the extra-polite “you” — you'd use it with a teacher, or a grown-up you just met, like your friend's mom or dad. Try it: ¿Cómo está usted? — ask a grown-up how they are, extra-politely.",
      "mnemonic": "Picture usted as the “handshake with a stranger” word — arm's-length and polite. Its informal counterpart, tú, is the “close friend” word — hug-distance and casual.",
      "usage_note": "Formal, respectful “you.” Use with strangers, elders, and authority figures. Regional note: in Costa Rica and parts of Colombia and Ecuador, usted (not tú) is the everyday default even among close friends and family — a pattern called ustedeo; elsewhere in Latin America and Spain, usted stays reserved for formal/unfamiliar contexts. When addressing an adult you don't know, usted is the safer default anywhere.",
